title: For Sale/Trade:  MAK 90 modifications
postcontent: OK folks, this is important so listen up.  This deals with modifying the MAK 90 and SKS type semi-autos.   There have been recent add here on this site, that appear to be totally illegal guns for sale.  I have corresponded with a couple such folks and they were simply folks that had no clue.  So, let me explain this just once.....a MAK 90 is covered by a 1989 federal law where George Bush 42 banned certain assault weapons by Executive Order and then Congress made that law effective forever and it is still in effect today and applies to every MAK 90 ever made.  It has nothing to do with the Bill Clinton Assault rifle ban that existed from 1994-2004 and which one presidental candidate wants to put back into law.....  the simple rule is that you cannot modify a MAK 90 in anyway whatsover unless you change out 5-6 parts with US made parts under federal law, 18 USC 922.....you cannot just change out the ugly thumbhole stock, it is a crime unless you change out enough other parts to make the new gun legal under 18 USC 922....I have a link to a blog that lists a 2005 BATF letter stating that "assembling a firearm" happens every time you replace a part....just contact me and I will send the link and others.  Also check Gunwiki or the SKS Boards for a list of what you need to do to stay legal...it matters.....don't do dumb stuff...email me for the link....or check falfile.com......it say not even a saiga with a straight stock can be replaced.....it is the official BATF ruling on replacing stocks.....

The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed.
